INSERT INTO `Xextended` (`NrArticle`, `IdLanguage`, `Fauthor`, `Fdate`, `Fintro`, `Ftext`) VALUES (136,4,'Mižkan Mi&#269;i&#263;-&#272;uri&#263;','2002-05-17','',''),(144,1,'Sobir Akhrarov','2002-05-28','The first Western forces for more than 2,000 years look set for a long stay in Kyrgyzstan, but Kyrgyz citizens aren\'t hearing much about it.','MANAS AIRPORT and OSH, Kyrgyzstan--At a press conference marking the 26-27 April visit of U.S. Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld to Kyrgyzstan, Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev drew parallels to a far more distant foreign army presence in these parts. Pointing to the most famous and successful soldier--Alexander the Great--he said that those who have invaded Afghanistan via Kyrgyzstan have triumphed in their campaigns.<BR>\n<BR>\n\"Those who bypassed Kyrgyzstan on their way to Afghanistan were not successful,\" the president warned, concluding that the Americans\' wise choice to use Kyrgyzstan as a staging ground left \"no doubt that Rumsfeld would be completely successful in Afghanistan.\" Considering that the last time Western troops made their way to Kyrgyzstan was more than 2,000 years ago with Alexander, the reach into antiquity wasn\'t so surprising.<BR>\n<BR>\n<!** Image 1><BR>\nMap of Kyrgyzstan.<BR>\nCourtesy of University of Texas.<BR>\n<BR>\nBut Rumsfeld, maybe not entirely comfortable with the Alexander comparison, responded that it is \"quite clear that the interests of the United States are notably different from those of Alexander the Great.\" Nevertheless--perhaps heeding Alexander\'s example--the United States is constructing a compound the size of nearly nine city blocks to fly missions into Afghanistan from Kyrgyzstan.<BR>\n<BR>\nEngineers and technicians are constructing the base piece by piece with building blocks ferried in large containers from Germany into the Manas civilian airport outside of Bishkek, the capital of Kyrgyzstan. Eventually the facility will have the capacity for 3,000 people and will include a field hospital, gyms, living quarters, and cafeterias. As more personnel, equipment, and aircraft arrive in Manas, the area is gradually turning into Ganci Air Base--a United States military stronghold. (The name is a tribute to Peter Ganci, the New York City fire chief who died in the World Trade Center attack on 11 September 2001.)<BR>\n<BR>\nWhen he visited Manas, Rumsfeld told the U.S. troops there--numbering approximately 1,000, with an additional 1,000 allied personnel--that the United States would remain in Kyrgyzstan \"as long as it takes\" to root out Al Qaeda and Taliban forces, whom he called \"mass murderers.\"<BR>\n<BR>\nThe U.S. and allied soldiers are using the base under a one-year agreement that can remain in force until either side decides to end it. Given the advantages to both sides, the cooperation seems unlikely to wind down any time soon, despite the precarious position that Kyrgyzstan\'s president has found himself in due to the U.S. presence. Russia, China, and Iran are all watching the small mountainous nation and its big new geo-strategic role. And Akayev\'s own people, who have not been kept very well informed about U.S. arrivals, may also object to Kyrgyzstan\'s powerful new friends once the length of the U.S. stay becomes clear.<BR>\n<BR>\nThe net gain--at least in the monetary sense--for Kyrgyzstan is not hard to ascertain. The United States pays from $3,000 to $7,000 per plane for landing and service fees. The average yearly salary in Kyrgyzstan is just over $2,000, and the economic situation is precarious, especially in the populous south. According to Osh Governor Naken Kasiev, more than 50 percent of the residents of the Osh region live in poverty. The unofficial numbers are even higher.<BR>\n<BR>\nIn addition, though no new foreign aid has been promised to Kyrgyzstan, hopes are high that the United States will increase aid in return for Kyrgyzstan\'s cooperation. The longer the stay, the more likely it is that American assistance dollars will flow into the country.<BR>\n<BR>\n<!** Title>WHO\'S WATCHING NOW?<!** EndTitle><BR>\n<BR>\nAll indications are that the United States has no immediate plans to leave the area. \"America will have a continuing interest and presence in Central Asia of a kind that we could not have dreamed of before,\" U.S. Secretary of State Colin L. Powell said in February. And it was widely reported in late April that the U.S. Defense Department is working to create a long-term military \"footprint\" in Central Asia. Beyond Afghanistan and the \"war on terror,\" Central Asia holds immense strategic interest for the United States, not least for its untapped energy reserves, and the region\'s rivals know it well.<BR>\n<BR>\nThe day before Rumsfeld\'s visit to Kyrgyzstan, Iranian President Mohammad Khatami--speaking in Kazakhstan, where the Unites States has been granted fly-over but not basing rights--said that Iran was concerned \"about the presence of armed forces of large non-local states in Central Asia.\" The Iranian president at that time called the U.S. presence \"a humiliation for the peoples of those states,\" but refrained from comments of that nature on a visit to Kyrgyzstan after Rumsfeld had left the country.<BR>\n<BR>\nStatements from Russian officials indicate Moscow\'s belief and hope that the American presence is connected only with the coalition in the war against terror--and will therefore end when the coalition does. In Kyrgyzstan, Moscow has taken steps to keep and strengthen its political, economic, and cultural clout, though some local observers decry the moves as awkward and rather late.<BR>\n<BR>\nRumblings in the Russian State Duma that Kyrgyzstan should pay back $133 million of its debt to Russia with proceeds from the money Kyrgyzstan was receiving from the military base was one such example. Ultimately, the IMF, with the support of Russia, agreed to restructure part of the debt in exchange for Kyrgyz assurances that the government will tackle corruption and economic stagnation, Argumenty i Fakty reported on 1 May. The offer was part of a larger scheme to offer IMF debt relief to the seven poorest countries in the former Soviet Union--Tajikistan, Uzbekistan, Azerbaijan, Armenia, Georgia, Moldova, and Kyrgyzstan.<BR>\n<BR>\n<!** Title>THE SILENT TREATMENT<!** EndTitle><BR>\n<BR>\nThe ramifications of any long-term U.S. military presence--the possible benefits to Kyrgyz citizens in the form of local jobs or foreign aid and the potential risks to Kyrgyzstan\'s bilateral relations with Iran and Russia in particular--haven\'t been covered much in the Kyrgyz media, though. Especially in the poverty-stricken southern part of the country, Kyrgyz citizens are being told little about it.<BR>\n<BR>\nAfter mass media representatives complained that there had been too little and too vague information about the U.S. presence in Kyrgyzstan, the U.S. Embassy invited a team from the popular OshTV Company--based in Kyrgyzstan\'s second-largest city, Osh--to fill the gap. Until then, southern Kyrgyz residents had heard about the U.S. base only through mass media headquartered mostly in northern Kyrgyzstan.<BR>\n<BR>\nThe TV team was given free rein to ask questions and film all of the facilities, including the surgical ward and even an equipment and weapons warehouse. The first question the TV team asked--echoing one of the first questions from the troops at Manas to Rumsfeld--was how long the U.S. military planned to stay in Kyrgyzstan. \"As long as it is needed,\" the engineering commander, Billy Montgomery, said, just as Rumsfeld would say later.<BR>\n<BR>\nOshTV also asked Montgomery if the U.S. army would assist Kyrgyzstan if religious extremists attack the southern part of the country again, as Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan (IMU) terrorists have done each summer since 1999. The Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan was created in 1996 and included veterans of the 1992-1997 civil war in Tajikistan. Montgomery said that he had no doubt that assistance would be provided, although he did not indicate if the United States would send its own troops to southern Kyrgyzstan. One unintended assist to the Kyrgyz government was the apparent death of IMU leader Juma Namangani, who was killed in a U.S. bombing raid in Afghanistan, along with several top lieutenants.<BR>\n<BR>\nSome Osh residents are now expressing hope that having the United States military in Kyrgyzstan could mean a summer without fear. That\'s something that Alexander the Great didn\'t offer.<BR>\n'),(145,1,'Akaki Gogichaishvili','2002-05-28','\r\n<i>Is Georgia\'s new mission to purge the Pankisi Gorge of Al Qaeda terrorists and Chechen rebels working? It seems not. As Rustavi 2\'s hard hitting news program, 60 Minutes, showed this month, senior Russian and Georgian officers continue to feed Chechen rebels with arms.<br />\r\n</i>','\r\nGeorgia forms a natural bridge through Russia\'s breakaway republic of Chechnya, Turkey and the Arab world, which makes it a natural channel for guns and fighters. And without doubt many fighters have slipped over the borders, and many guns have been smuggled. It\'s a common story for every Georgian journalist. Our television channel, Rustavi 2, and most newspapers, have carried story after story about how Georgian soldiers have turned the war in Chechnya into a lucrative business, selling munitions and trafficking weapons, and how the Chechens have turned to drugs and kidnapping to raise funds for guns.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBut for years, the Georgian government has turned a blind eye and sealed its lips on the issue. Then came reports in February that Al Qaeda fighters were in Georgia, and that the Americans were willing to help, and fund, efforts to smoke the fighters out of their bases in the Pankisi Gorge. Eyes opened and lips were unsealed. Action was agreed on, and President Eduard Shevardnadze announced, &quot;Yes, I can confirm&quot; that Ruslan Gelaev, a Chechen field commander and the most wanted &quot;terrorist&quot; in Russia, was in Georgia. &quot;I regard him as an intelligent person,&quot; Shevardnadze added.<br />\r\nHere was a good opportunity to counter Russian influence, the Georgian political establishment thought--just as turning a blind eye to the Chechens in Georgia had been a way to wreak some sort of revenge on Russia for its open support of the separatist Georgian republic of Abkhazia.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOf course the Russians have always complained about Georgian involvement in arming the Chechens. But their own public secret is that the Russian military, like the Chechens\' Arab supporters, have been a major source of arms and ammunition for the rebels.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHere was a good story, we at 60 Minutes thought: how the Russians created a problem and the Americans solved it for them. A good story indeed, if we could find the facts and film the transfer. No one had done that before.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSo his arrival was a surprise, and a perfectly timed one, at that. Suddenly, right on our doorstep, we had a Chechen security officer willing to talk about how arms were transferred from Russian military bases to the Pankisi Gorge. He said a Georgian general was the broker. The general had not delivered on his last promise. It had cost the Chechens $50,000 to buy the guns they never received, and after months of waiting, they wanted revenge.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe ID he presented indicated that he was Auib Paikaev, a captain who had already served five years in the service of the Ministry of National Security of the Republic of Ichkeria, the Chechen name for Chechnya. It said he was 34, but he looked to be in his late forties: his forehead was deeply wrinkled, and his face was criss-crossed with scars. The impression was fiery. He was hook-nosed and red-bearded, and his greenish eyes flashed as he explained his business. The general was protected by the government and a squad of armed bodyguards. Blood revenge was impossible, but, if we wanted, we could film him in secret when he next met the general.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe agreed, of course.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<!** Title>TRAPS... AND TRAPS<!** EndTitle><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe meeting was set to take place two days later, so we had time to check files on the Georgian general. He was Tristan Tsitelashvili, 45, a field commander during the civil war in Abkhazia in 1992 and, until 2001, the head of a major military detachment, the 11th Brigade. He had been fired for being unable to account for a huge amount of armaments, including armored vehicles, tanks, mortars, the lot.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe defense minister\'s own assistant, Alexander Mchedlishvili, told us it was common knowledge in the army that Tsitelashvili was involved in the illicit arms trade, but the official investigation had been unable to prove it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThat wasn\'t quite true, Gia Jikia, the army\'s prosecutor general and head of the investigation, told us. &quot;Yes, we had sources saying Tsitelashvili was selling arms, but just small amounts of arms, nothing important. And besides,&quot; he added, &quot;you know the military are underpaid? And, after all, he had fought for the country. To be frank, we decided not to prosecute him.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThat was not all. The Interior Ministry had twice charged General Tsitelashvili with kidnapping--but in both cases, the charges had been dropped. We asked to have access to those files, but they were gone. &quot;The National Security Ministry took the files and hasn\'t returned them,&quot; explained Paata Gomelauri, a spokesperson for the Interior Ministry. We turned to the National Security Ministry, but all our efforts were fruitless. There was no response at all.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn fact, it was the National Security Ministry that General Tsitelashvili named as his protector--or &quot;roof&quot; (krysha ) in Russian criminal slang--when he next saw Aiub Paikaev. They met in a caf�. Paikaev had a camera hidden in his sweater. Another camera was at the far end of the caf� and a third camera with our crew was waiting in a car with tinted windows just outside the caf�.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;My friend,&quot; the general began, &quot;the fact that I am here shows how I trust you. My &quot;roof,&quot; the chief of military counter-intelligence, warned me that you might be cooperating with people from Rustavi 2 to harm me.&quot; That was old news to us, as we knew our offices and visitors were under constant surveillance. But the general did not take the warnings seriously, and the arms dealing began:<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGeneral: &quot;I\'ll give you the owner of the Sarajishvili Company [a famous local alcohol producer]. He\'s worth much more than I owe you guys, so be sure to pay me back when you get the ransom.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nChechen officer: &quot;Only if this is a serious offer, because otherwise we\'d prefer to wait for the arms as long as it takes you get them for us.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGeneral: &quot;No, no, I swear to God, I\'ll give you the guy. You\'ll be told when and where to pick him up, and I\'ll be nearby with my people to support you in case anything unexpected happens.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nChechen officer: &quot;Very good. Listen now, we need some ammunition meanwhile, not much--just three \'zincs\'(slang for standard-size ammunition boxes) and quickly tomorrow.&quot; (We had asked to be able to film a scene in which arms were sold from the Russian military warehouse.)<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGeneral: &quot;No, not tomorrow--the day after tomorrow. Meet me at the Ergnety market (an unofficial market for smugglers on the border in the Tskhinvali region of the breakaway republic of South Ossetia where goods from Russia are sold on the cheap) and I\'ll bring you ammunition. It will cost $600, plus some money for my guys to take you with the zincs to Pankisi.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nChechen officer: &quot;Remember the good times? We used to bring arms from Tskhinvali two or three times a day...&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGeneral: &quot;Sure I do. Looks like new players are getting in on the market. Have you heard about this Shota guy? Don\'t trust him, he is a government plant; I warn you, no dealings with him.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nJust at this point, a group of about 10 policemen began to check all the cars in front of the caf�. Such checks are nothing unusual in Georgia. What it meant, though, was that our crew was forced out of the car. When the general saw them, he exploded in fury. &quot;Did you bring \'Rustavi 2\' here?&quot; he demanded. Aiub played innocent and flatly denied everything. The General left and promised to call Aiub later.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLater that evening, a sharpshooter sent a bullet through the window of our office, up on the 16th floor. Luckily, no one was in the room. That made a big splash in all the local newspapers the next morning, but we said nothing in the hope that we would still be able to film the arms transfer in Tskhinvali.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFive days passed with no news from the general. Finally, he called Aiub and said they should meet in Ergnety in three hours\' time and that he would bring the &quot;zincs.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt takes two hours to drive to Ergnety so we set out straight away to map out the site. But it was a trap. The moment they arrived, our two crews were arrested by the South Ossetian military, thrown behind bars, and beaten. It took phone calls from the defense and foreign ministries to free them later that day.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAiub arrived separately in Ergnety, but the general did not come. It was clear there was no value in waiting, so we put the material on air, accompanied by our interview with Aiub.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe government did not react on the broadcast. It became obvious then that nothing would happen to the general, but that something might happen to Aiub. So he left his apartment and hid with friends. We warned him not to call our office, as we knew our phones were bugged and any call could be traced but he called the next day to ask if there was anything new.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe very same day he was attacked near his friend\'s apartment. Three men beat him unconscious, but his life was saved by passersby. When the police came, they arrested him. The attackers had fled. The next day, with the help of human rights activists, we managed to free him.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe police did not investigate the attack. Aiub had four fractures in his skull, and both his legs and one hand were broken. We approached the National Security Ministry, the military prosecutor\'s office, and the Interior Ministry, saying that Aiub was willing to cooperate with the government to expose the whole network of illicit arms deal in Pankisi. No one replied.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTwo days later, on 4 April, Aiub was kidnapped from his hospital bed. The general himself called Aiub\'s friend to tell him that Aiub had been killed. The general offered Aiub\'s friend three choices: to start working for him on arms deals, to leave the country, or to be killed. He left for Azerbaijan.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMeanwhile, two months have passed since the United States said it would send troops, but none are here. The new talk may be of rooting out terrorism, but the old corrupt ways and blind eyes persist.<br />\r\n'),(146,1,'Abdumannob Polat','2002-05-29','<I>Over-dramatizing the human rights situation in Uzbekistan will not make the situation better.<BR>\n</I>','WASHINGTON--Exaggeration is unfortunately commonplace in reporting and advocating on human rights in Uzbekistan. While it\'s a fact that the government of President Islam Karimov is known for its poor human rights record, the truth is not simplistic, and the situation in Uzbekistan is not black and white.<BR>\n<BR>\nIn an 8 January article published in the Online Journalism Review , author Andrew Strohlein claims that \"not only are print and broadcast media rigidly censored, but the Internet is as well.\" However, as Joshua Machleder of Internews-Uzbekistan noted in a 14 January post on the FSUMedia listserve, \"The Uzbek Internet is rather healthy and well, and many news sites based in Uzbekistan are publishing critical material from here, and people here have access to them.\"<BR>\n<BR>\nWhile he did go on to caution that there is \"a movement on the part of the government to create a powerful server that could exercise control over the ability of Uzbekistan\'s citizens\" to access the Internet, he emphasized that at present \"there is no systematized Internet censorship in Uzbekistan.\"<BR>\n<BR>\nRight now it seems that the Internet is still not a significant headache for the Uzbek government. It is true that there is no truly independent mass media in Uzbekistan--except possibly a few semi-independent and censored (like any other media outlets in the country) local TV and radio stations and a small number of print media with limited circulation.<BR>\n<BR>\n<!** Image 1><BR>\nUzbek Pesident Islam Karimov<BR>\n<BR>\nFor print and broadcast media, then, the situation is more dire, but exaggerated reports of its demise are not the answer. In an otherwise balanced article in The Moscow Times from November, Matt Bivens engaged in an inaccurate assessment common in reporting on Uzbekistan: \"There is no free press or political opposition; Karimov\'s critics are jailed or exiled.\"<BR>\n<BR>\nOn this point, I have to return to the words of Internews\'s Machleder, who wrote in the same post referred to earlier: \"That statement does a disservice to the many talented and brave Uzbeks working within the country\'s borders who stick their necks out in the fields of human rights and media to work for change. Uzbeks are not a downtrodden nation, subservient to their president. There are people in the country--smart, with democratic spirits--who want to live and survive on their native soil, and who have had to compromise somewhat in order to fight for change. Maybe they have modified their aims and lowered their expectations--but they are still making small gains toward democratic reforms.\"<BR>\n<BR>\nIndeed, many critics of Karimov are in exile or in jail, and some have even died in jail. But it is also true that many other critics of Karimov in Uzbekistan are not in jail. And most of them--particularly if we speak about activists with secular-democratic leanings--are not in exile, either.<BR>\n<BR>\nIt is also truethat there is no legalized political opposition in Uzbekistan. However, most of the members of the key opposition groups, Birlik and Erk, are living in the country, and their activities are tolerated, though not legalized. They often meet in Tashkent with high-ranking Western diplomats and politicians and give interviews to foreign media, including those that broadcast in Uzbekistan, such as Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty, the BBC, Voice of America, and Iranian Mashhad Radio.<BR>\n<BR>\nMost of their statements are critical of Uzbek government policies, and the authorities more or less tolerate such activities. Of course, there have been several cases of harassment for giving interviews to foreign media, mostly when the person interviewed is a little-known local resident from an area far from the capital.<BR>\n<BR>\n<!** Title>THE RIGHTS OF THE OPPOSITION<!** EndTitle><BR>\n<BR>\nMost secular-democratic opposition activists and human rights campaigners--as a general rule, the same people, many of whom have been my colleagues and friends for years--who are living in Uzbekistan are able to exercise their right to travel throughout Europe and the United States to lobby for their interests and criticize their own government, and then return to their homeland and continue their activities.<BR>\n<BR>\nThat is true not only for Birlik members but also for Erk, whose leader, Mohammed Solih, was accused by the government of masterminding explosions that killed 16 people and injured scores of others in the Uzbek capital, Tashkent, in February 1999. Though Karimov\'s government failed to present adequate evidence against Solih in the case, an Uzbek court sentenced Solih in absentia to 15 and a half years in prison in connection with that bombing. And there are allegations that he had close connections to the Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan for years. There are credible reports that he led what he later called a \"bodyguard training\" of 21 young Uzbeks in Turkey in 1994, and the Karimov government and some independent observers suspected that those activities were actually terrorist training.<BR>\n<BR>\nDespite those allegations and charges, most Erk members in Uzbekistan--including Solih\'s closest associates--are tolerated. However, several people, including three of Solih\'s brothers, are in jail. It is widely held that Solih\'s brothers are innocent and that their imprisonment is Karimov\'s reaction to allegations against Solih, who is living in exile in Norway and therefore is unavailable for trial.<BR>\n<BR>\nEven Otanazar Oripov--the general secretary of Erk, a close associate and friend of Solih, and a former political prisoner himself--has been able to travel freely outside Uzbekistan and to act as Erk\'s spokesperson in Uzbekistan. He has been in close contact with Solih and has met with him several times in Turkey and Europe. The week after the Uzbek president\'s upcoming trip to Washington on 11 and 12 March, Oripov is expected to visit the United States to brief Americans involved in democracy-building and human rights promotion in Central Asia on the state of democracy in Uzbekistan.<BR>\n<BR>\nIt is believed that Tashkent has not acted against other members of the opposition mainly due to Western pressure on the government as a condition of aid. But that does not mean that current positive developments--even when such positive signs could be seen as small--should be ignored.<BR>\n<BR>\nCertainly much needs to be done to encourage respect for democracy and human rights in Uzbekistan. However, lobbying for positive changes should not stumble into the realm of exaggeration. I am not saying that Uzbekistan is a free country--just that the reporting about its problems should be fair.<BR>\n'),(147,1,'Seymur Selimov','2002-05-29','<I>In the days preceding this week?s talks on Caspian Sea borders--which broke down on 24 April without agreement--Iran made new, aggressive claims of sovereignty. Its challenge is not just to Azerbaijan, but to the West, as well.<BR>\n</I>','BAKU, Azerbaijan--Ever since the break-up of the Soviet Union, the five countries that share the Caspian shoreline have been trying to reach a decision on how to share the sea and its oil-rich bed. Yesterday, the latest, long-delayed effort to reach a deal broke down after a two-day summit in Ashgabat, the capital of Turkmenistan. The reasons why are still unclear. However, the negotiations were expected to be rocky, partly because, going into discussions, Iran made it clear that it prefers preemptive action, rather than compromise, as the best way to secure its interests. If its strategy succeeds, the loser may not just be Azerbaijan, but the United States as well.<BR>\n<BR>\nOn 5 March, Iran\'s oil minister, Bijan Namdar-Zangani, declared that Iran would soon begin prospecting for oil in areas of the sea jointly claimed by Azerbaijan and Iran. Just days earlier, a small, unexpected sign of progress had appeared during a gathering of CIS officials in Almaty on 27-28 February; Russia\'s deputy foreign minister, Victor Kaluzhny, declared that a settlement was \"practically ready.\" But when the Iranians, as promised, began to drill at the end of March--and when Namdar-Zangani told the BBC that Iran would not allow any other country to explore for oil in the 20 percent of the sea area to which Iran is laying claim, effectively declaring 7 percent of the sea off-limits--expectations for the Ashgabat talks were lowered.<BR>\n<BR>\nGoing strictly by its share of the shoreline, Iran has rights to just 13 percent of the sea\'s resources. This latest strategic move seems like a deliberate challenge to that math, for several reasons.<BR>\n<BR>\nFirst, Teheran\'s move reversed its initial position on this question. Until recently, Teheran had said no country should exploit any oilfield in disputed territory until a final decision was made. When, in July 2001, an exploration vessel owned by British Petroleum entered disputed waters to carry out research on the Sharq-Alov oil field, Iran sent its gunboats in, claiming the boat was in Iranian waters.<BR>\n<BR>\nSecond, the move puts Azerbaijan in an extremely awkward position. Azerbaijan has already signed contracts with foreign companies, including U.S. oil giants, to exploit the disputed oilfields, raising the prospect that disputes over who controls which field will move from the negotiating table to the high seas. Though the big internationals signed the contracts knowing that the border question was still open, if Baku does ultimately concede these fields to Iran, Azerbajan will look like an unreliable business partner, incapable of holding its own--and could, as a result, be forced to say goodbye to serious investment in oil sector for some time to come.<BR>\n<BR>\nThird, Iran\'s move comes just as work is about to begin on the construction of a new pipeline to take Azeri oil to Turkey (via Georgia) and onward to the world market. Some of the most valuable fields lie in disputed waters. Teheran may believe that if it takes a hard line, the pipeline plans will have to be suspended--if only for a brief time--and that the amount of oil flowing westward via Azerbaijan will fall sharply. It may have been emboldened by the gunboat incident last summer; British Petroleum stopped prospecting in the Sharq-Alov oil field.<BR>\n<BR>\nFourth, Namdar-Zangani\'s 5 March announcement came on the eve of a widely publicized visit to Iran by Azerbaijan\'s President Heidar Aliev. There are few possible explanations for the timing, argues the independent Azeri political scientist Kerim Selimov. One is that, \"for some reason, Teheran [was] interested in turning the trip into a farce or to force Aliev to be appear to accept Iran\'s actions.\" Selimov argues that \"first and foremost,\" the move was a ploy to force Aliev not to visit Teheran, giving Iran \"the opportunity to pin all the blame for the deterioration of the situation in the Caspian onto Azerbaijan.\"<BR>\n<BR>\n<!** Title>The country\'s aggressive stance<!** EndTitle> may partly reflect its increasing isolation. In recent weeks and months, Russia, Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan have signed--or agreed in principle--a series of bilateral agreements. Iran is suddenly faced with a more united opposition to its proposals than ever. Moreover, its sole remaining potential ally--Turkmenistan--has the smallest claim to the sea and may find it difficult to throw its support behind Iran, which was not part of the Soviet system and, in the post-11 September world, finds itself more alone than ever.<BR>\n<BR>\nThe Azeri political scientist Rasim Musabekov doesn\'t give Iran\'s aggressive Caspian strategy much chance of success. One reason is that, he claims, the country lacks the technology and expertise to make a seismic survey of the sea or to develop its resources.<BR>\n<BR>\nNonetheless, the drilling is certainly undermining relations between Iran and Azerbaijan. The traditionally difficult relations between the two countries had already been strained this year by the Iranian defense minister\'s recent visit to Armenia. Another source of aggravation, Musabekov asserts, are \"calls in Iran to open a \'second front\' against the American and Western interests in the Caspian if the United States presses them harder and takes military action hostile to Iran.\"<BR>\n<BR>\nSo far, the United States shows few signs of backing down in the face of an Iranian challenge. On 12 March, the U.S. State Department\'s senior official on Caspian Affairs, Stephen Mann, indicated that the development of disputed Caspian oilfields could go ahead even before the border questions were settled--and that countries such as Kazakhstan have already been doing so.<BR>\n<BR>\nMann said that \"none of the possible forms of agreement on the division of the Caspian Sea should interfere with the transportation of Caspian oil\" to the world markets. Washington therefore appears to be giving its backing to the official position of Baku and the de facto situation in the Caspian Sea. And, if the words of Deputy Secretary of State Richard Armitage on 7 March are a reliable indication, the United States \"will not stand idly by and watch [Iran] pressure [its] neighbors.\"<BR>\n'),(150,1,'Michael Pascoe','2005-07-15','\r\nLast night\'s Media Watch tackled the strange business of how the now 100% foreign owned and controlled News Ltd can launch a new newspaper in Australia in clear breach of the treasurer\'s foreign investment policy. ','\r\nHow very fortunate for Peter Costello to have News Ltd\'s lawyers around\r\nto explain what the government\'s foreign investment guidelines really\r\nmean. Otherwise the Foreign Investment Review Board might make a\r\nmistake – and Rupert wouldn\'t be pleased.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLast night\'s <a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s1411250.htm\">Media Watch</a>\r\ntackled the strange business of how the now 100% foreign owned and\r\ncontrolled News Ltd can launch a new newspaper in Australia in clear\r\nbreach of the treasurer\'s foreign investment policy.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMurdoch\'s control of most of the country\'s newspapers was grandfathered\r\nwhen the present mishmash of foreign and cross-media ownership rules\r\nwere introduced by the Keating Government in 1993. But the little\r\noddity in those rules is that a newspaper\'s “foreignness” is only the\r\n“non-portfolio” part of the shareholding, so in News Corp\'s case, only\r\nthe Murdoch and Malone interests were counted as foreign when News Corp\r\nwas nominally an Australian company. Murdoch\'s lawyers also managed to\r\nconvince FIRB to count both the voting and non-voting shares as\r\ncontrolling capital, despite the non-voters obviously not having\r\ncontrol – which is why Murdoch issued them.\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\nBut what happened when News Corporation became a totally foreign entity\r\nlast year? After all, News Limited is now owned by a 100% non-portfolio\r\nforeign investor – News Corp.\r\n<br /><br /><span style=\"font-style: italic;\">\r\n\r\nMedia Watch </span>quoted the relevant bit of the treasury\'s policy document\r\nthat FIRB guidelines ( here) apply to: “All proposals by foreign\r\ninterests to acquire an interest of 5% or more in an existing newspaper\r\nor to establish a new newspaper in Australia.”\r\n<br />\r\nWhy then is this foreigner allowed to launch a new newspapers when\r\nanother foreigner – Spaniard Javier Moll – is being prevented from\r\nlaunching a daily newspaper in Adelaide in competition with America\'s\r\nCitizen Murdoch?\r\n<br /><br />\r\nLast year when I was grappling with the non-portfolio issue and the\r\nstrange treatment of the Moll family for Sunday Sunrise, FIRB wouldn\'t\r\ntalk and directed all questions to Costello\'s office where a flack who\r\nclearly didn\'t know suggested I contact News Corp. The flack was right\r\n– much wiser to ask the organ grinder than the monkey.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nIt looks like Media Watch had the same problem, turning to News Ltd\'s\r\nlawyers for this quote: “MX is not subject to consideration under the\r\ngovernment\'s foreign investment policy. The relevant policy applies to\r\nthe establishment of a new business. It does not apply to the expansion\r\nof an existing business. The reference to a new newspaper in clause 34\r\nof the policy summary is a reference to a new newspaper business.”\r\n<br /><br />\r\nWhat News really means is that the words “new newspaper” don\'t mean\r\n“new newspaper” – they mean “new competitor with Murdoch interests.”\r\nAnd the federal government wouldn\'t want that.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nMeanwhile, back in Adelaide where Rupert\'s empire started, Javier Moll\r\nwas allowed to buy the monthly Adelaide Review, and even received FIRB\r\npermission to take it fortnightly last year as long as it doesn\'t carry\r\n“news.” Murdoch\'s Advertiser has thrown everything but the kitchen sink\r\nat the upstarts, launching its own review insert and slashing\r\nadvertising rates.\r\n<br /><br />\r\nMoll is left to fight with both hands tied behind his backs. He wants\r\nto start a daily in Adelaide first, then in that other Murdoch monopoly\r\nnewspaper town, Brisbane. Maybe he should try hiring Murdoch\'s lawyers.'),(151,1,'Steve Mayne, crikey.com.au','2005-07-15','\r\nThe saga of the Goanna, the Costigan Royal Commission and alleged tax avoidance schemes had Crikey reaching for Paul Barry\'s biography of Kerry Packer yesterday after the death of Gold Coast property developer Brian Ray. And what an amazing trip down memory lane it was, replete with big names of today starring in a Royal Commission that started back in 1980.','\r\nThe saga of the Goanna, the Costigan Royal Commission and alleged tax avoidance schemes had Crikey reaching for Paul Barry\'s biography of Kerry Packer yesterday after the death of Gold Coast property developer Brian Ray. And what an amazing trip down memory lane it was, replete with big names of today starring in a Royal Commission that started back in 1980.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRobert Richter QC has just got Mick Gatto off a murder charge and handled Steve Vizard\'s ASIC deal. More than 20 years ago he was the Special Prosecutor appointed to pursue tax issues arising from the Costigan Royal Commission and he had Brian Ray in court for a mammoth 54 days of evidence in 1985 which saw Ray committed to trial on the &quot;exceedingly strong probability&quot; that he was involved in a &quot;dishonest and unscrupulous scheme... to deprive the Commonwealth of income tax.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhen he finally beat the rap in 1987, Ray threw a big party on the Gold Coast attended by Sir Joh Bjelke-Petersen, John Singleton and Kerry Packer, where Sir Joh declared: &quot;I have always been proud to have Brian as a friend and to know he is on my team.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe big question which remains unresolved to this day was the exact involvement of Kerry Packer in Ray\'s tax schemes. Frank Costigan, Douglas Meagher QC and Brian Toohey, the then editor of Fairfax\'s National Times, certainly attempted to fit Kerry Packer up with all sorts of crimes and misdemeanors that were completely false. Who can forget the 8,000-word public denial Australia\'s richest man issued in November 1984, two weeks after Toohey went all out with the half-baked, half-cocked and frankly embarrassing case summaries of the supposedly secret volume nine from Costigan\'s final report.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHowever, Barry leaves the reader with the clear impression that Kerry Packer, who was represented by Malcolm Turnbull at the Royal Commission, was the secret financier and private backer of a dodgy tax avoidance scheme promoted by Ray. Richter and Costigan certainly believed that to be the case. The best theory on the delivery of $225,000 in cash from Brian Ray to Kerry Packer was that it was his share of the profits from the scheme.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter shepherding through the Steve Vizard matter, Richter is presumably an expert on secret $1 million transfers to disguise public attention. But one mystery that Brian Ray will presumably take to his grave is the question of who was behind Progress Credits Pte and the $922,000 it transferred into Brian Ray\'s bank account on 21 November 1979 to fund what Paul Barry called &quot;quite obviously a dreadful rort.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNo-one argues that Packer instructed Ray to talk to his Sydney solicitors, Allen Allen &amp; Hemsley, which did indeed instruct an offshore trustee company called Universal Corporate Services to transfer the money through a separate offshore shelf company Progress Credits Pte to Brian Ray\'s account.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter three consecutive days of evidence in October 1983, Ray signed an authority permitting Costigan to seize all Progress Credits documents. Lo and behold, Allens immediately sent the file from its Sydney office to Singapore, so Costigan dispatched Les Lasry (who conducted the Ambulance Royal Commission for Steve Bracks), Rick McDonnell and Victorian policeman Frank Green to retrieve it.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter getting agonisingly close, the file was then spirited away to Hong Kong where it was retrieved by one Bruce McWilliam from Allens, who later admitted in court he was acting for Kerry Packer, even though Packer continued to deny he was behind the scheme or had done anything wrong. These days McWilliam is a senior executive at the Seven Network and has just sold his Vaucluse property for $18 million. Maybe he could give the story to Today Tonight if things get really ugly in the forthcoming legal battle over Foxtel.'),(153,1,'Michael Pascoe','2005-07-15','\r\n\r\nLast night\'s Media Watch tackled the strange business of how the now 100% foreign owned and controlled News Ltd can launch a new newspaper in Australia in clear breach of the treasurer\'s foreign investment policy.<br />','\r\n\r\nHow very fortunate for Peter Costello to have News Ltd\'s lawyers around to explain what the government\'s foreign investment guidelines really mean. Otherwise the Foreign Investment Review Board might make a mistake – and Rupert wouldn\'t be pleased.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nMurdoch\'s control of most of the country\'s newspapers was grandfathered when the present mishmash of foreign and cross-media ownership rules were introduced by the Keating Government in 1993. But the little oddity in those rules is that a newspaper\'s “foreignness” is only the “non-portfolio” part of the shareholding, so in News Corp\'s case, only the Murdoch and Malone interests were counted as foreign when News Corp was nominally an Australian company. Murdoch\'s lawyers also managed to convince FIRB to count both the voting and non-voting shares as controlling capital, despite the non-voters obviously not having control – which is why Murdoch issued them.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBut what happened when News Corporation became a totally foreign entity last year? After all, News Limited is now owned by a 100% non-portfolio foreign investor – News Corp.<br />\r\n<br /><!** Image 1  align=right  alt=\"Sydney from Bondi\"  sub=\"Sydney from Bondi\">\r\nMedia Watch quoted the relevant bit of the treasury\'s policy document that FIRB guidelines ( here) apply to:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n    “All proposals by foreign interests to acquire an interest of 5% or more in an existing newspaper or to establish a new newspaper in Australia.”<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhy then is this foreigner allowed to launch a new newspapers when another foreigner – Spaniard Javier Moll – is being prevented from launching a daily newspaper in Adelaide in competition with America\'s Citizen Murdoch?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLast year when I was grappling with the non-portfolio issue and the strange treatment of the Moll family for Sunday Sunrise, FIRB wouldn\'t talk and directed all questions to Costello\'s office where a flack who clearly didn\'t know suggested I contact News Corp. The flack was right – much wiser to ask the organ grinder than the monkey.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt looks like Media Watch had the same problem, turning to News Ltd\'s lawyers for this quote:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n    “MX is not subject to consideration under the government\'s foreign investment policy. The relevant policy applies to the establishment of a new business. It does not apply to the expansion of an existing business. The reference to a new newspaper in clause 34 of the policy summary is a reference to a new newspaper business.”<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat News really means is that the words “new newspaper” don\'t mean “new newspaper” – they mean “new competitor with Murdoch interests.” And the federal government wouldn\'t want that.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMeanwhile, back in Adelaide where Rupert\'s empire started, Javier Moll was allowed to buy the monthly Adelaide Review, and even received FIRB permission to take it fortnightly last year as long as it doesn\'t carry “news.” Murdoch\'s Advertiser has thrown everything but the kitchen sink at the upstarts, launching its own review insert and slashing advertising rates.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMoll is left to fight with both hands tied behind his backs. He wants to start a daily in Adelaide first, then in that other Murdoch monopoly newspaper town, Brisbane. Maybe he should try hiring Murdoch\'s lawyers.<br />'),(154,1,'Martin Callinan, onlineopinion.com.au','2005-07-16','\r\n<!** Image 1  align=left  >Two weeks ago the US Senate passed an energy Bill to diversify away from fossil fuels and offered formal recognition that mandatory action on climate change was necessary. As the largest per capita greenhouse gas emitter in the world, a champion of voluntary management of greenhouse gas emissions and a steadfast opponent of market-based limitations and incentives - Australia now stands alone.','\r\n<!** Image 2  align=left  alt=\"Nuclear power use large cooling towers to dispose of excess heat.\"  sub=\"Nuclear power use large cooling towers to dispose of excess heat.\">\r\n“If this looks like Kyoto, the answer is \'No\',” President Bush said in an interview recently in response to a question on a potential climate change agreement at the recent G8 summit. That’s the same old line. The new line was the president’s support for efforts to “diversify away from fossil fuels”.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis is not just rhetoric. Two weeks ago the US Senate passed an energy Bill to diversify away from fossil fuels and offered formal recognition that mandatory action on climate change was necessary. Where does this leave Australia?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs the largest per capita greenhouse gas emitter in the world, a champion of voluntary management of greenhouse gas emissions and a steadfast opponent of market-based limitations and incentives - Australia now stands alone. Now no developed country stands either beside or behind Australia on energy or climate matters.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe new US legislation will require energy suppliers to source at least 10 per cent of their entire supply from renewable sources by 2020. To help businesses meet this requirement, the Senate Finance Committee approved US$14.4 billion for tax incentives and credits, particularly for renewable sources such as solar, wind, bio-diesel and ethanol production. These tax breaks over the next decade will foster domestic and industrial energy efficiency, hybrid fuel transport, export markets and more efficient fossil fuel technology.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn awkward contrast, Australia’s mandatory renewable energy target is set at 9,500 GWh, which will equate to less than 2 per cent by 2010 or near 1 per cent, by 2020. Labor’s alternative policy is to more than double the target to a proportional 5 per cent by 2010.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe US Energy Policy Act of 2005 was passed with overwhelming bipartisan support (85 to 12). The Bill is now being reconciled with the version passed by the House of Representatives in April. A National Energy Plan was the president’s first priority when he came to office, since then two proposed energy Bills have failed to pass congress. The Bill passed this week will be on President Bush’s desk before August.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith crude oil contracts at US$60 a barrel and the cost of renewable energy sources dropping, the US Senate has taken a big and logical step forward. The Bill and its considerable funding have clear ramifications for Australia because US lawmakers have stepped ahead of the Bush Administration.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf US action to support renewable energy doesn’t concern the Howard Government, then the president’s re-posturing in the lead-up to the G8 Summit and the changing nature of US approach to climate policy should.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDuring debate on the Bill, a “Sense of the Senate on Climate Change” resolution was passed, with the support of 12 Republican Senators, saying “that congress should enact a comprehensive and effective national program of mandatory, market-based limits and incentives on emissions of greenhouse gases that slow, stop, and reverse the growth of emissions ...”<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Bush Administration’s voluntary approach to address climate change was debated and considered to possess zero prospect of ever reducing greenhouse emissions.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith express reference to countries like Australia, the resolution also held the mandatory national program should function in a manner that “will encourage comparable action by other nations that are major trading partners and key contributors to global emissions”.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSuch legislative development in the US also raises questions about how the Howard Government balances frank policy advice with the impulse to follow its political instinct. Australia, unlike the US, has no mechanism for the creation of law that is not the explicit political will of the leader of the administrative branch of government. How Australia’s energy and climate policy have become disconnected from the rest of the world’s actions deserves some scrutiny, particularly in light of the government’s new-found control of the senate.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSuch political progress in the US is courtesy of its normal checks and balances but it has unsheltered and consequently isolated Australia’s energy and climate policy. Time inevitably founders all policy based upon reality-aside ideology. Is this the case for the Howard Government or is it just an unusual irony that it is the US showing Australia the way forward on climate change?<br />'),(155,1,'Steve Mayne','2005-07-30','\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\"><!** Image 1  align=right  >As Steve Vizard\'s tangled web begins to unwind, Crikey has been forced to establish a new section called &quot;Vizardry&quot; in the daily email to cover the businessman\'s dubious dealings. See what was run in the first instalment of Vizardry below:\r\n\r\n</p><p>Character is destiny, according to the Greek philosopher Heraclitus. But what about a name?\r\n\r\n</p><p>According to our Oxford Dictionary, a Vizard is a &quot;disguise&quot; or &quot;visor or mask,&quot; and the verb to vizard means &quot;to conceal or disguise (something) under a false outward show or appearance; to represent falsely or suspiciously.&quot;\r\n\r\n</p><p>As the mask is lifted even more, we\'ve been forced to create a new section in the Crikey Daily, which we\'ve called Vizardry (a word that isn\'t in the dictionary). Our only excuse is that we were completely Vizarded.</p>','\r\n<p style=\"font-style: italic;\"><!** Image 1  align=right  >As Steve Vizard\'s tangled web begins to unwind, Crikey has been forced to establish a new section called &quot;Vizardry&quot; in the daily email to cover the businessman\'s dubious dealings. See what was run in the first instalment of Vizardry below:\r\n\r\n</p><p>Character is destiny, according to the Greek philosopher Heraclitus. But what about a name?\r\n\r\n</p><p>According to our Oxford Dictionary, a Vizard is a &quot;disguise&quot; or &quot;visor or mask,&quot; and the verb to vizard means &quot;to conceal or disguise (something) under a false outward show or appearance; to represent falsely or suspiciously.&quot;\r\n\r\n</p><p>As the mask is lifted even more, we\'ve been forced to create a new section in the Crikey Daily, which we\'ve called Vizardry (a word that isn\'t in the dictionary). Our only excuse is that we were completely Vizarded.</p>\r\n\r\n<!** Title><b>Steve Vizard\'s serial insider trading</b><!** EndTitle><br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<i>Crikey Daily - Tuesday, 26 July</i><br />\r\n\r\n<i><br />\r\nBy Stephen Mayne</i><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe Fairfax press was comprehensively scooped today as <i>The Australian</i> and the <i>Herald Sun</i>\r\ntogether produced stories revealing Steve Vizard\'s secret trading\r\nvehicle, Creative Technology Investments, bought and sold shares in\r\nanother five companies in which he was likely to have possessed\r\nsensitive information.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<i>The Australian\'s</i> <a href=\"http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5744,16049805%255E2702,00.html\">front page story</a> was the clearest cut, explaining how Vizard bought $150,000 worth of shares in The Seven Network at $5.31 a piece in December\r\n1999 when British television production company Granada Media was negotiating to pay a premium for a 9.1% stake.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nGranada had previously paid an excessive $25 million for Vizard\'s\r\nArtist Services and was proposing a merger with Seven\'s production\r\noperations to stem the losses. Vizard was chairman of Granada Australia\r\nand also chaired the Granada-Seven joint venture vehicle so he\r\npresumably was well across the negotiations.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nTwo months later in February 2000, Granada announced its $148 million\r\ninvestment\r\nat $6 a share and this significant vote of confidence in Kerry Stokes\'s\r\nleadership sent Seven shares soaring 25c to $5.78 on the day it was\r\nannounced.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe <i>Herald Sun</i> revelations were equally interesting,\r\nrevealing that Vizard bought into PMP, ERG and two American companies,\r\nExodus and Extant, all of which had dealings with Telstra, ranging from\r\njoint ventures to the telco buying a 20% stake..<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThe stories are based on ASIC documents presented to the Federal Court\r\nwhich seems curious because Vizard only plea-bargained on the dealings\r\nin Computershare, Keycorp and Sausage. Therefore, it looks like ASIC\r\nfelt they potentially had eight cases against Vizard which would have\r\ncarried a maximum fine of $1.6 million, based on $200,000 for each\r\noffence.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThere is now absolutely no doubt about it, that Steve Vizard was a\r\nserial inside trader and his ducking, weaving, lying and negotiating to\r\nstay out of jail is an outrage.<br /><b><br />\r\n</b><b><!** Title>More Vizard consulting shenanigans?<!** EndTitle></b><i><br />\r\n<br />\r\nBy Crikey reporter Sophie Vorrath</i><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nDespite denials from all directions, Crikey has received yet another\r\ntip about Steve Vizard\'s intriguing web of business alliances. We\'ve\r\nalready written about the possible connection between Vizard, an\r\numbrella company called Communicate Pty Ltd and a Melbourne advertising\r\nagency called See. Since Vizard began his unpaid (we are told)\r\n&quot;consulting&quot; work at See, the agency has won accounts for the National\r\nAustralia Bank, the Melbourne Commonwealth Games and the National\r\nGallery of Victoria. <br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nCoincidence? Maybe. And here\'s another one – sent by an anonymous tipster yesterday – to add to the list:<br /><blockquote>I read with interest your piece on Steve Vizard and his\r\nrelationship with See Life Differently (which is the self-conscious\r\nfull name for the advertising company to which you refer as &quot;See&quot;).\r\nVizard can occasionally be spotted swanning around in See\'s trendy\r\nbayside warehouse-conversion offices. I am unaware of whether or not he\r\nhas a direct financial stake in See, but See\'s employees sometimes\r\nrefer to him as &quot;the silent partner.&quot; <br />\r\n\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>Interestingly, See carried out advertising work for the\r\nVictorian Major Events Corp while Vizard was VMEC\'s chairman. The work\r\ndone was related to the 2007 World Swimming Championships, and guess\r\nwho was also chairman of Melbourne 2007 World Swimming Championships\r\nCorp at that time? Yep, it was Vizard. </blockquote><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<b><!** Title>Steve Vizard\'s amazing (and profitable) art collection<!** EndTitle></b><br />\r\n<i><br />\r\nBy Stephen Mayne</i><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nSteve\r\nVizard\'s spin doctor Mike Smith defiantly declared last week that his\r\nclient had &quot;donated millions of dollars worth or art&quot; through his\r\nvarious charitable and philanthropic ventures. But exactly how he did\r\nit is a little hard to fathom.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nThere\'s no doubt that the Steve Vizard Foundation owns one of\r\nAustralia\'s most impressive contemporary art collections worth many\r\nmillions of dollars, including works\r\nby Tracey Moffatt, Ricky Swallow, Howard Arkley, Patricia Piccinini and\r\nmany others.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIt was assembled for him by the Sir Ian Potter Museum of Art at\r\nMelbourne University. These experts have spent many hundreds of hours\r\nworking for Vizard, and two years ago even produced a fabulous 174-page\r\nglossy book, <i>See Here Now: Vizard Foundation Art Collection of the 1990s</i>, cataloguing every work his charity has acquired. The opening acknowledgements include the following:<br /><blockquote>The collection itself was developed by curatorial committee\r\nmembers Eritus Professor Margaret Manion AO, Frances Lindsay, Steve\r\nVizard AM, Dr Roger Benjamin, Dr Alison Inglis, Merryn Gates and Dr\r\nChris McAuliffe. Staff of the Ian Potter Museum of Art and the\r\nUniversity of Melbourne Conservation Service have undertaken\r\nsubstantial work in the administration and display of the Vizard\r\nFoundation Art Collection over the past decade.<br />\r\n</blockquote>\r\nOf course, all of this adds to the value and prestige of the collection – but who gets the benefit?<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nCrikey\'s famous sister-in-law Patricia Piccinini finds one of her most prominent works, <i>Psychogeography</i>,\r\non the cover. And it so happens that Vizard\'s purchase has been\r\nincredibly profitable, with the Melbourne University team picking it up\r\nfor him for just $2,000 in the late 1990s. This is what we carried in\r\nCrikey Daily on 30 November 2003 about the sale of one of the prints\r\nthat Vizard owns:<br /><blockquote>Patricia\'s success in Venice appears to be causing a flurry\r\nof sales in the secondary market as owners of her work make\r\nextraordinary profits. Mike Gibson\'s wife has doubled her money in\r\nlittle more than 12 months with the hammer price of $67,500 for\r\nPsychogeography at Sotheby\'s last week. To work out the purchase price\r\nyou need to add the buyers premium of about 8% and GST, so the new\r\nowner of Psychogeography paid more than $80,000.<br />\r\n</blockquote>\r\nSteve Vizard made a promise at Melbourne Airport ten days\r\nago: &quot;I want to be crystal clear: I am deeply, deeply sorry and I\r\nintend to work actively over the rest\r\nof my life to try to set things right.&quot;<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n Given that Margaret Manion was one of three character referees in court\r\nfor him last week, we look forward to the former funny man announcing\r\nthat he is donating the entire collection to the institution which\r\nincurred so much cost putting together something so profitable for him.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n We\'re not talking about lending it or donating some of it. Get it\r\nvalued, Steve, and donate the lot – lock, stock and barrel. That would\r\nbe a good first step down the road to recovering your reputation, and\r\nmight stop people saying you\'re an aggressive tax planner with deep\r\npockets and short arms.<br />\r\n\r\n<i>\r\n<br />\r\n</i><b><!** Title>Has ASIC declared open season on insider trading?<!** EndTitle></b><br />\r\n<i><br />\r\nCorporate lawyer Adam Schwab writes:</i><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIf ASIC (and the DPP) hadn\'t blundered enough by failing to bring\r\ncriminal charges against Vizard, they topped it off by a staggering\r\nperformance in the Federal Court. <br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\nThe statement of agreed facts between\r\nVizard and ASIC informed everyone what Vizard did. His actions, which\r\nhe admitted to, were a very serious criminal offence. The only reason\r\nhe wasn\'t charged criminally is that for some reason, the DPP and ASIC\r\nfailed to read an evidence law textbook or were outwitted by the likes\r\nof Richter and Zwier. <br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n That said, given that ASIC has been publicly humiliated in failing to\r\ncharge Vizard with\r\na criminal offence, you\'d think ASIC would at least have a crack at the\r\nmaximum possible civil penalty. Instead, ASIC has recommended a fine of\r\na mere $130,000 per offence – far less than the $600,000 maximum – and\r\na mere five-year ban from directorships. <br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNeil Young outlined two of ASIC\'s reasons for not seeking the maximum\r\npenalty to the Federal Court – each reason provided by ASIC is wrong in\r\na legal and perhaps more importantly, a moral sense.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<i>1. Vizard\'s Apparent Contrition</i><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nNeil Young noted that &quot;Mr Vizard deserves credit for (his contrition,\r\nand it would) merit a substantial reduction (in his sentence).&quot;\r\nHowever, Vizard wasn\'t overly contrite. He:<br /><ul type=\"disc\">\r\n<li>Spent five years fighting ASIC\'s charges. \r\n</li><li>Hired a massive legal team to try to avoid any penalty. \r\n</li><li>Did not apologise for his actions until well after he was charged by ASIC. \r\n</li><li>Did not turn himself in, but was rather dobbed in by his allegedly crooked former bookkeeper. \r\n</li><li>Entered into a sweetheart deal with regulators because his corrupt accountant refused to testify. </li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese\r\nare not the actions of a man who is &quot;contrite.&quot; Rather, they are the\r\nactions of a man who did everything in his power to avoid the correct\r\npenalty for his clearly criminal actions and merely apologised in order\r\nto reduce his penalty. As the clichê goes, Vizard was not sorry about\r\nwhat he did, he was sorry about getting caught.<br /><i><br />\r\n\r\n2. Vizard had already suffered because of his diminished reputation</i><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nClearly this is one that you won\'t find in the criminal law textbooks.\r\nVizard\'s reputation was damaged because he committed a crime, concealed\r\nit, then arranged a sweetheart\r\ndeal to avoid criminal sanctions. His public position is not a\r\nmitigating factor – if anything, the fact that Vizard was in such a\r\npublic position may have even added to his penalty.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIf Vizard had committed armed robbery, presumably his reputation would\r\nalso have been tarnished. However, one would doubt whether the Supreme\r\nCourt would take that into consideration in determining a reduced\r\npenalty – why is the situation different for a &quot;white collar&quot; crime?<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nIf a tarnished reputation is grounds for a reduced penalty – ASIC is\r\neffectively conceding that if you are rich and famous, you will get a\r\nlesser penalty than if you are an average battler. That is because an\r\naverage battler would not be able to rely on the &quot;tarnished reputation&quot;\r\ndefence in order to have his or her penalty reduced.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nWhile ASIC, as a regulator, does not set a precedent in a case like\r\nVizard\'s (as a court would) – it would reek of favouritism if ASIC\r\nadopted one stance for celebrity crooks like Vizard and another stance\r\nfor your unknown insider trader. If ASIC has set an unofficial\r\nprecedent, it would mean that any investment banker or lawyer acting on\r\na deal who uses information to insider trade (but does so by getting a\r\nmate to set up a company and undertake the trades on their behalf)\r\nshould receive the\r\nsame light penalty that Vizard looks like getting.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nTherefore, ASIC has effectively declared that it\'s open season for\r\ninsider trading. So long as the insider gets someone else to undertake\r\nthe trades for them and that the other person refuses to testify, the\r\nworst that can happen is a small fine and a ban from being a company\r\ndirector. <br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n\r\nFurther, like the Fares brothers (from NAB) and Vizard (who made a\r\npaper profit of $150,000 on his dodgy trades before stupidly not\r\nselling all his share during the boom) showed – there are some very,\r\nvery handsome profits to be made from insider trading information and\r\nthe risk of penalty is very, very low.<br /><br />\r\n\r\n<b><!** Title>Defenceless Vizard copping it from all sides<!** EndTitle></b><br />\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<i>Crikey Daily - Wednesday, 27 July</i><br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<i>By Stephen Mayne</i><br /><br />Poor old Steve \r\nVizard has tied himself up in so many knots that he finds himself unable to \r\ndefend himself against allegation after allegation. Refusing to give evidence on \r\nthe grounds of self-incrimination is damning in itself, but when you risk \r\nperjury charges and potential criminal insider trading charges by uttering \r\nanything more, you\'ve just got to lie down and cop it.<br /><br />Vizard\'s former \r\nbookkeeper Roy Hilliard certainly took the opportunity yesterday to introduce \r\nnew allegations against his former boss as his feisty counsel, Peter Hayes QC, \r\nemployed all sorts of rhetorical flourishes in front of a large media \r\npack.<br /><br />Having been scooped by News Ltd on Tuesday over \r\nthe five other examples of potential inside trading, the Fairfax press produced \r\na classic over-reaction today as <i>The AFR</i> declared on page one that \r\nHilliard had made &quot;sensational claims,&quot; while <a href=\"http://theage.com.au/news/national/vizard-absent-as-qc-lets-loose-new-accusations/2005/07/26/1122143849429.html\" title=\"http://theage.com.au/news/national/vizard-absent-as-qc-lets-loose-new-accusations/2005/07/26/1122143849429.html\"><i title=\"http://theage.com.au/news/national/vizard-absent-as-qc-lets-loose-new-accusations/2005/07/26/1122143849429.html\">The \r\nAge</i></a> also put these &quot;explosive allegations&quot; on the front.<br /><br />The best \r\nFairfax comeback by <i>The Age</i> was <a href=\"http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/more-investments-while-director-revealed/2005/07/26/1122143849435.html\" title=\"http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/more-investments-while-director-revealed/2005/07/26/1122143849435.html\">this</a> \r\n\r\nLeonie Wood story today pointing out that Vizard instructed Greg Lay to buy \r\n$150,000 worth of shares in US data transmission company Extant just three days \r\nbefore Telstra announced a $50 million investment. This was just after Vizard \r\ntravelled with the Telstra board to North America.<br /><br />Hilliard went through \r\na long committal hearing, so you would think he would have dropped out the \r\nsecret offshore bank accounts to dodge tax a little earlier. The offshore \r\nproposal was apparently first mooted by Vizard\'s old Herbert Geer &amp; Rundle \r\nmate Guy Jalland, but it never went ahead as Vizard decided he wanted more \r\ncontrol over it, which is why the onshore Creative Technology Investments was \r\nestablished instead.<br /><br />If Vizard really approved every single Hilliard \r\ntransaction, why did he demand Westpac repay $2 million and call in private \r\ninvestigators? The most feasible explanation is that Vizard was indeed doing his \r\naggressive tax planning, but Hilliard helped himself to some of the proceeds \r\nalong the way. The figure of $400,000 has been mentioned, but what happened to \r\nthe other $2.6 million, much of which was actually money that should have gone \r\nto the tax man?<br /><br />Vizard has never been asked whether Hilliard actually \r\npaid back most of this missing $2.6 million, yet a star-struck Westpac handed \r\nover $2 million just five days after the powerful Melbourne establishment figure \r\ncomplained.<br /><br />Stand by for Westpac to take action in the courts to force \r\nVizard to return some of this money. Westpac still has the mortgage over \r\nVizard\'s $6 million Toorak home, so watching this relationship will be one of \r\nthe interesting next chapters in this extraordinary saga.<p />'),(157,1,'Sophie Black, crikey.com.au','2005-08-05','It\'s not often that Aussies get top billing on the <a href=\"http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/1742423C-EBDE-4CDE-B9DB-7310AAA43DA3.htm\"><i>Al Jazeera</i> news bulletin</a>\r\nbut that\'s what happened yesterday when claims by former ASIO officer\r\nMichael Roach – that suspected Islamic militants are based in\r\nAustralia\'s two main cities – ran as the top story.<br />\r\n<br />','<i>by Crikey reporter Sophie Black<br />\r\n<br />\r\n</i>It\'s not often that Aussies get top billing on the <a href=\"http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/1742423C-EBDE-4CDE-B9DB-7310AAA43DA3.htm\"><i>Al Jazeera</i> news bulletin</a>\r\nbut that\'s what happened yesterday when claims by former ASIO officer\r\nMichael Roach – that suspected Islamic militants are based in\r\nAustralia\'s two main cities – ran as the top story.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRoach retired less than two years ago after a 30-year career at ASIO,\r\nnamely as an assistant director with ASIO\'s T4 group, responsible for\r\nsecurity of government facilities. He first made the\r\nclaims on <i><a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2005/s1428699.htm\">Lateline</a></i>\r\nwhen he told Tony Jones there could be up to 60 Islamic extremists\r\nliving in terrorist cells in Australia. Roach also suggested that\r\npolice and security guards should be targeting men of Middle-Eastern\r\nappearance who are acting suspiciously – there\'s another name for it:\r\nracial profiling. <br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;Unfortunately, Middle-Eastern people are going to be approached more\r\noften than not and that\'s just the way it goes at the moment. We can\'t\r\ndo anything about it,&quot; he told <i>Lateline</i>. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nAttorney-General Philip Ruddock\r\nhas dismissed the prospect of racial profiling, saying that using\r\nracial features to identify terrorist suspects would leave Australia\r\nvulnerable and exposed to attack. And according to last night\'s <i>Lateline</i>,\r\nit seems Roach, too, is backing down from his earlier comments – &quot;let\'s\r\njust take this racial card right out of this because this is what\'s not\r\ngood for their community and it\'s not good for Australia.&quot;<br />\r\n<br />It\'s not often that Aussies get top billing on the <a href=\"http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/1742423C-EBDE-4CDE-B9DB-7310AAA43DA3.htm\"><i>Al Jazeera</i> news bulletin</a>\r\nbut that\'s what happened yesterday when claims by former ASIO officer\r\nMichael Roach – that suspected Islamic militants are based in\r\nAustralia\'s two main cities – ran as the top story.<br />\r\n\r\n<br />But, as a subscriber pointed out, there\'s a glaring discrepancy between\r\nthe government\'s past denunciation of government &quot;whistleblowers&quot;\r\nand Australian Federal Police commissioner Mick Keelty\'s <a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2005/s1429697.htm\">confirmation</a>\r\nyesterday of Roach\'s claims. &quot;It\'s something that\'s not news to the\r\nintelligence agencies and the AFP (Australian Federal Police),&quot; Keelty\r\ntold <i>Lateline</i>, &quot;We\'ve been aware for some time roughly the\r\nnumber of people who have trained overseas, and they\'ve been the focus\r\nof the attention of both ASIO, the AFP and also the state police in our\r\njoint operations.&quot; <br />\r\n<br />\r\nASIO has refused to comment on Roach\'s claims, so why is Keelty confirming this sensitive information?\r\n'),(158,1,'The Reader, crikey.com.au','2005-08-10','\r\nIsrael pulls out of the Gaza and the West Bank.\r\n','\r\n<div align=\"center\"><!** Image 1  align=none  alt=\"Garang\"  sub=\"Garang\"></div>The significance of Israel\'s withdrawal from Gaza is obvious, says <a style=\"color: rgb(255, 34, 136); text-decoration: none;\" href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/08/09/AR2005080901169.html\">David Makovsky</a>\r\nin The Washington Post today: for the first time since the 1967 war,\r\nIsraeli hawk Ariel Sharon is setting about to dismantle Jewish\r\nsettlements in an area that Palestinians see as part of their ultimate\r\nstate. But as the start date for the move looms, the “how?” and the\r\n“what then?” are far from clear. This week\'s Reader cover story\r\nexplores the mixed feelings coming from both sides of the wall.<br /><div align=\"left\">\r\n<br />\r\nBack home, Federal Parliament has resumed and, as Christian Kerr\r\nwrites, things got\r\npretty ugly during the first session of the new age of Liberal Party\r\nSenate majority. Perhaps it would do them good to stop quibbling and\r\npause to reflect on the tragedy currently gripping Niger, where 2.5\r\nmillion people are facing death by starvation.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd as always, for your further enjoyment, we\'ve cast a wide net to\r\nbring you the latest word on the demise of the metrosexual, the success\r\nof Shepparton\'s Muslim community, yet another death-knell for rock and\r\nroll, the wrap on the thrilling second Ashes Test, and the inside story\r\non the current state of play at Rupert Murdoch\'s business empire.</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n');
