INSERT INTO `Xfastnews` (`NrArticle`, `IdLanguage`, `Fdate`, `Fintro`, `Fbody`) VALUES (111,1,'2002-03-29','\r\nIsraeli troops took over most of Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat\'s Ramallah compound on Friday, fighting room-to-room and arresting as many as 70 people, Israel Defense Forces said.<i><br />\r\n</i>','\r\nThe Palestinians disputed the number of arrests, but said one Arafat aide had been arrested at a home outside the compound. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne of his aides said Arafat was holed up in an office on the second floor of a building. He has been confined to Ramallah by Israel since December. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nAlso on Friday, Al Aqsa Martyrs Brigades -- the military wing of Arafat\'s Fatah movement -- claimed responsibility for the blast that killed at least two Israelis in Jerusalem. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nAn Israeli officer had been killed during firefights with Palestinians armed with automatic weapons, the IDF said. At least four Palestinians were killed in the fighting, according to Arafat\'s spokesman Nabil Abu Rudeineh. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nU.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell, during a Friday news conference, condemned the Passover violence against Israelis and called on Arafat to take action against those responsible. <br />\r\n<br />\r\n&quot;The United States condemns these acts and those responsible for them,&quot; Powell said. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nPowell said U.S. Middle East envoy Anthony Zinni would remain in the region. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nSince the beginning of the Passover holiday on Wednesday night, Palestinian groups have carried out three terror attacks against Israelis that resulted in 28 Israeli deaths and more than 100 injuries.'),(143,1,'2002-05-28','\r\nA new World Health Organization (WHO) study on tobacco consumption, harmful effects, and control efforts in the 48 countries of the WHO European Region will be launched at the WHO European Ministerial Conference for a Tobacco-Free Europe in Warsaw on 18-19 February. ','\r\nA new <!--** Link external \"http://www.who.dk\"-->World Health Organization  (WHO) study on tobacco consumption, harmful effects, and control efforts in the 48 countries of the WHO European Region will be launched at the WHO European Ministerial Conference for a Tobacco-Free Europe in Warsaw on 18-19 February. Representatives of 46 countries, among them 24 health ministers and 13 secretaries of state and other high-level delegates, will gather there to review findings, share experience, and strengthen their coordinated action against tobacco in Europe.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe new WHO European Tobacco Control Report includes in-depth information about consumption, deaths related to tobacco use, trends among different age and socioeconomic groups and between men and women, tobacco industry marketing strategies, and policies regarding smoke-free public space . The findings summarized in the report are based on the abundant evidence in the European Tobacco Control Policy Database, to be launched in Warsaw as well. The database includes country-specific information about tobacco prevalence, policy measures, and economic indicators and provides journalists across Europe with valuable statistics on tobacco issues that many, especially in Eastern Europe, are unlikely to obtain through government channels.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe report looks specifically at tobacco-control policies related to advertising bans, support for smokers to quit, market regulation by means of targeted price and taxation policies , product control, and toxic-constituents control. That links to comprehensive tobacco control and to measures that have proven extremely effective, resulting in significant reductions in consumption and harm in some countries.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTaken as a whole, the new WHO data show that key tobacco-control challenges reach far beyond national borders. International action is necessary to combat a rise in cigarette smuggling and increasingly aggressive and effective transnational tobacco industry marketing. The study makes clear that countries need to adopt new tactics. The results of some EU directives show that international legally binding treaties are effective.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<!** Title>At the conference<!** EndTitle>, ministers will explore how they can build upon the experience of their countries and their experience with transnational legislation and provide strong leadership for the Framework Convention on Tobacco Control (FCTC), currently being negotiated by WHO\'s 191 member states. The FCTC will be the world\'s first multilateral international treaty on a major health issue and will have WHO as its secretariat. It will include a set of rules and regulations to govern the global use and spread of tobacco and tobacco products in the future, addressing issues including marketing, agricultural diversification, smuggling, taxes, and subsidies.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhile the WHO European Region comprises 15 percent of the planet\'s population and 15 percent of all the smokers in the world, it suffers 32 percent of the global burden of diseases related to smoking.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTobacco products are responsible for 1.2 million deaths (14 percent of all deaths) in Europe each year. Experts project that, unless more effective measures are implemented, they will cause 2 million deaths (20 percent of all deaths) each year by 2020. Until recently, this epidemic of chronic disease and premature death mainly affected rich countries, but it is rapidly shifting to low- and middle-income countries in the region.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nBut something can be done, and the ministerial conference will play an important part in the global anti-tobacco campaign.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNew data from 10 European countries where advanced and efficient tobacco-control policies have been implemented show a sustained decrease in the number of tobacco-related deaths during the last 10 years. Five countries (Finland, Iceland, Slovenia, Sweden, and Great Britain) reported a decrease in tobacco consumption to below 25 percent (compared to a regional average of 30 percent). In Warsaw, ministers will discuss ways all countries can achieve reduced consumption levels.<br />\r\n'),(149,1,'2002-11-19','\r\n<table cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"0\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><!** Image 1  align=left  ></td><td style=\"vertical-align: top;\">This article tells you more about the Campare.org demo server. Live and learn.</td><td><br /></td></tr></tbody></table><br />','\r\nWelcome to the <!--** Link external \"http://www.campware.org\" TARGET \"_blank\"-->Campware.org\'s demo server. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nYou will be able to play around pretty extensively on this server. The price for freedom is that from time to time we will have to send cron to restore the database to its original form, which means that your logins will be lost along with content that you have created on this server.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<!** Image 2  align=left  alt=\"Campware logo\"  sub=\"This is caption text\">Preview should work for the fastnews publication, if you use article types: fastnews and extended. Other publications present on this server were created by your fellow testers, and please go ahead and try creating one as well. If you\'d like to tell us more about your experiences with CAMPSITE, or you would like to work on it in a more permanent environment, please drop us an e-mail at <!--** Link external \"mailto:contact@campware.org\"-->contact@campware.org. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you\'d like to know more about the way CAMPSITE works, check out the HTML version of the CAMPSITE manual <!--** Link external \"http://www.campware.org/look/campware/download/CAMPSITE-manual.html\" TARGET \"_blank\"-->here.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nYou will be able to input your content in any language or character sets. For example, you could write this:<br />\r\n<br />\r\nНесколько лет назад для хранения картофеля я изготовил разборный деревянный ящик из досок (его можно сделать и из реек). Под него для воздухообмена уложил два слоя кирпича, а на них - слой рубероида<br />\r\n<br />\r\nor this:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div align=\"right\">وأكد متسناع أنه سيدعو الفلسطينيين، حال فوزه، للعودة إلى مفاوضات السلام على أساس &quot;المشروع الذي طرحه الرئيس الأمريكي السابق جون كلينتون&quot;، مشيرا إلى أن عدم تحقق تقدم في تلك المباحثات سيدفعه إلى فرض &quot;حدود أمنية لن تترك مستوطنات إسرائيلية خارجها.&quot; <br />\r\n</div><br />\r\n<br />\r\nor this:<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPolicisté v Praze 9 zneškodnili funkční výbušný systém, který lehce poškodil jednu kolej. V pondělí večer podle policie někdo vrakem auta zjevně úmyslně zablokoval trať mezi Vršovicemi a Krčí.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nor this:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<div align=\"right\">רקובה ארק ענצמ .םיבושיי 240-כב תויפלק 269-ב םימייקתמ סירמיירפה<br />\r\nםינעוטש הלאכ שי&quot; .םירקסב יסחיה ונורתי תורמל ,תויפלקל עיגהל ויכמותל <br />\r\nתא דוע ךכל םיפיסומ םא .תוריחבה םויב םיזוחא 10 טעמכ הווש ןוגראש <br />\r\n</div><br />\r\nor this:<br />\r\n<br />\r\nΠιεστικός έως παρακλητικός, για να δοθεί ημερομηνία στην Τουρκία για έναρξη των προενταξιακών διαδικασιών εμφανίστηκε στην Αθήνα ο Ρετζέπ Ταγίπ Ερντογάν.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nPlease feel free to add your language or script of choice below.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<!** Title>FIRST SUBHEAD (page break)<!** EndTitle><br />\r\n<br />\r\nSome text could go here as well.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<!** Title>SECOND SUBHEAD<!** EndTitle><br />\r\n<br />\r\nAnd some text could go there too.'),(156,1,'2005-08-03','A freedom of speech debate is currently raging in Australia over the racist statements of a Macquarie University academic.<br />','<i>Martin Vukoja, a former student of Professor Andrew Fraser, writes:</i><p>\r\n\r\nI was a student in Associate Professor Andrew Fraser\'s Anglo-American Constitutional History course at Macquarie University in 2002 and found many of the views he expressed entirely repugnant and undeniably racist, although I do support his right to express these views in both public and private arenas. Here\'s one of the more outrageous theories that I recall him spouting.</p><p>\r\n\r\nDuring a discussion on the relationship between the US Constitution and the institution of slavery, he attempted to mount a tortured defence of the concept of race-based segregation on the basis that African Americans actually benefited from their forced separation from white Americans. The fact that a strong family ethic and an entrenched religious faith within African American communities apparently arose as a result of segregation seemed to wholly justify the policy in his opinion. I sincerely doubt that African American communities would agree. That someone would attempt to justify a cruel and brutal policy that ensured the continued subjugation of one race at the hands of another by referring to the perceived &quot;benefit&quot; to the suppressed group clearly expressed to me the depth of his delusion and racism.</p><p>\r\n\r\nHis disconnectedness from the actual reality of segregation was marked. Did he actually care that the philosophical (and indeed biological) underpinning of race-based segregation was the superiority of the white race over all others and the potential for contamination of the white race through social contact with African Americans? Did he care about the impact of a policy that attempted to reinforce the goodness of racial &quot;purity&quot; and the ultimate deviance of anything not resembling the privileged majority? From his clearly expressed opinions, I garnered the distinct impression that he saw nothing wrong with the policy of race-based segregation and this was no doubt the impression that he wished to convey with this nasty and sinister exercise in racial hatred.</p>');
